Powered by RubiQube Ad Network Wilfred Ndidi Ndidi was called up to the Super Eagles on October 8, 2015, making his debut in the friendly game against DR Congo, and playing again a few days later in the 3–0 win against Cameroon, when he replaced John Mikel Obi in the 63rd minute. He was selected by Nigeria for their 35-man provisional squad for the 2016 Summer Olympics. In May 2018 he was named in Nigeria’s 23-man squad for the FIFA World Cup. • Oghenekaro Etebo Etebo made his debut on July 27, 2013 against Côte d’Ivoire in a 2–0 loss in Abidjan during the 2014 African Nations Championship qualification. He also played against Jordan in an international friendly on October 23, 2013. In December 2015, he helped the Nigerian U-23 team to the Africa Cup of Nations triumph in Senegal; finishing top scorer with five goals, including a brace in a 2–1 win against Algeria in the final. team to a bronze medal finish. He was in Nigeria’s 23-man squad for the 2018 FIFA World Cup in Russia. Etebo started all three of Nigeria’s group matches. • John Ogu In March 2013, Ogu was called up for a 2014 FIFA World Cup qualifier. He debuted against Kenya in a 1–1 draw, where he was used as a substitute to replaced Victor Moses. On May 31, 2014 Ogu scored his first international goal against Mexico in a friendly game which held at the Reliant Stadium in Houston. On June 9, late Stephen Keshi selected him as one of 23 players for the 2013 FIFA Confederations Cup. On 18 March 2015, he was called up for the friendly matches against Bolivia and South Africa. In May 2018 he was in Nigeria’s 23-man squad for the World Cup. • Forwards • Ahmed Musa On August 5, 2010, Musa debuted for Nigeria in a qualification match for the 2012 AFCON against Madagascar. In April 2011, he was included in the U-20 team for the 2011 African Youth Championship qualifiers. In August 2011, he represented Nigeria U20 in the 2011 FIFA U-20 World Cup in Colombia, where he scored three goals in five matches. He was called up to Nigeria’s 23-man squad for the 2013 AFCON. He scored in a 4–1 semifinal defeat of Mali and appeared as a substitute against Burkina Faso in the final, as the Super Eagles won their third continental title. At the 2013 FIFA Confederations Cup, he started in all three matches. And was named in the 2014 FIFA World Cup. • Victor Osimhen Osimhen, 21, first represented the country at the 2015 FIFA U-17 World Cup in Chile that the country won.He won the Golden Boot and Silver Ball awards. Osimhen made his senior debut in a 3–0 friendly win over Togo on June 1, 2017. He missed out on Nigeria’s 2018 FIFA World Cup campaign after his inconsistent season at Wolfsburg.Following a successful start to his loan spell at Charleroi, he was recalled by Gernot Rohr for the November 2018 international break, starting their friendly win over Uganda. • Moses Simon Moses Simon, 24, plays for the Nigeria selection. He received his first call-up by coach Daniel Amokachi in March 2015 and made his debut on the 25th of the same month in an international friendly against Uganda, when he replaced Anthony Ujah after 59 minutes in the game.Simon scored his first goal for Nigeria in an international friendly against Niger on September 8, 2015, the second in a 2–0 win. He was selected by Nigeria for their 35-man provisional squad for the 2016 Summer Olympics. In May 2018 he was named in Nigeria’s preliminary 30-man squad for the 2018 FIFA World Cup in Russia. However, he did not make the final 23 due to injury. • Henry Onyekuru Onyekuru, 22, is a Nigerian professional footballer who plays as a forward for Galatasaray, on loan from English Premier League (EPL) club, Everton, and the Nigeria national team. Onyekuru was called up for the Super Eagles camp in May 2017. He made his senior debut for Nigeria in a 3–0 friendly win over Togo on June, 1 2017. • Odion Ighalo On March 24, 2015, after a series of strong performances for Watford, newly appointed Nigeria interim coach, Daniel Amokachi selected Ighalo for the first time, and the latter stated, “I feel good because it is my dream to play for my country”. Ighalo, 30, won his first cap two days later, starting in a 0–1 friendly home loss to Uganda. Ighalo was one of three overage players named in Nigeria’s squad for the 2016 Olympic Games in Brazil. In June 2018, he was named in the 23-man squad for the upcoming edition of the FIFA World Cup in Russia, making his first appearance in the competition by playing 73 minutes in the 0–2 group stage defeat against Croatia; in October, he revealed that his family had received death threats after he failed to score in the tournament. Ighalo scored seven goals in the 2019 AFCON qualification campaign, the most by any player, to help Nigeria qualify for the finals in Egypt later that year. • Alexander Iwobi Iwobi, 23, started as a youth international for England, with whom he won the Victory Shiield of 2011. Iwobi went on to play for Nigeria. He made his senior debut for the Super Eagles on October 8, 2015, replacing Ahmed Musa in the 57th minute of a 2–0 friendly defeat to DR Congo in Vise, Belgium. He was selected by Nigeria for their 35-man provisional squad for the 2016 Summer Olympics. He was not a part of the 18-man final squad. In August 2017 Iwobi pulled out of Nigeria’s squad for that month’s World Cup qualifiers due to injury. On October 7, 2017, Iwobi scored for Nigeria in a 1–0 win over Zambia to secure the Super Eagles a spot in the 2018 FIFA World Cup in Russia. He was named in Nigeria’s 23-man squad for the 2018 FIFA World Cup in Russia. He said that the team needed to learn from its performance after going out in the group stages. In April 2019, he said he wanted to emulate his uncle, Austin ‘Jay-Jay’ Okocha by winning the Africa Cup of Nations. • Samuel Kalu On December 9, 2015, Kalu, 22, signed a two-year contract with the Slovak side AS Trencin. He made his professional debut for Trenčín against ŠK Slovan Bratislava on February 27, 2016. On January 4, 2017, he was transferred to Belgium top division club, KAA Gent.] On August 6, 2018, Kalu signed for Lique 1 side, Bordeaux, signing a five-year contract. On October 13, 2018, he scored his first international goal with the Nigeria senior national team against Libya. He scored the final goal in a 4–0 victory. • Paul Onuachu Onuachu, 25, moved to Danish club, FC Midtjyland in 2012, on a scholarship, from their affiliate team in Nigeria, FC Ebedei. He was a prolific scorer for their youth team, and Countdown To The 32nd Africa Cup Of Nations ‘Super Eagles Out To A Make A Statement’